<section xml:id="sec-sums-products-of-modules">
	<title>Sums, products, and direct sums</title>
	<introduction>
		Throughout this section we assume that <m>M</m> is a left module over a ring <m>R</m>. For some non-empty indexing set <m>I</m>, let <m>M_i</m> (<m>i\in I</m>) be left <m>R</m>-submodules of <m>M</m>.
	</introduction>
	<definition xml:id="def-sums-fo-module">
		<title>(Sum of submodules)</title>
		<statement>
			The sum of <m>R</m>-submodules <m>M_i</m> is the submodule generated by <m>\bigcup_{i\in I}M_i</m>. It is denoted by <m>\sum_{i\in I}M_i</m>. Thus
			<me>\sum_{i\in I}M_i=\left\{\sum_im_i:m_i\in M_i\;\text{are such that all but finitely many}\;m_i\;\text{are zero}\right\}</me>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="def-product-of-modules">
		<title>(Product of modules)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>(N_i)_{i\in I}</m> be a family of left modules over a ring <m>R</m>. We give the Cartesian product <m>\prod_{i\in I}N_i</m> an <m>R</m>-module structure by defining addition and multiplication as follows.
			<me>(x_i)+(y_i)=(x_i+y_i)\quad\text{where}\; x_i,y_i\in N_i</me>
			For any <m>r\in R</m> and any <m>(x_i)\in\prod_{i\in I}N_i</m>, the scalar multiplication is defined by
			<me>r\cdot (x_i)=(r\cdot x_i)</me>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="def-projection-maps">
		<title>(Projection maps)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>(N_i)_{i\in I}</m> be a family of left modules over a ring <m>R</m>. For each <m>i</m> we get the family of <m>R</m>-module homomorphism
			<me>\pi_i\colon\prod_{k\in I}N_k\rightarrow N_i\quad\text{given by}\;(x_k)_{k\in I}\mapsto x_i.</me>
			An <m>R</m>-mod homomorphism <m>\pi_i</m> is called the <term>projection homomorphism</term>.
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="def-direct-sum">
		<title>(Direct sum of modules)</title>
		<statement>
			Consider a family <m>(N_i)_{i\in I}</m> of left modules over a ring <m>R</m>. The <term>direct sum of <m>(N_i)_{i\in I}</m></term> is the following submodule of <m>\prod_{i\in I}N_i</m>.
			<me>\bigoplus_{k\in I}N_k=\left\{(x_k)_{k\in I}\in\prod_{k\in I}N_k:\pi_i((x_k)_{k\in I})=0\;\text{except for a finite number of indices}\right\}</me>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<convention>
		<statement>
			Consider <m>R</m> as a left module over itself. We denote by <m>R^{(n)}</m> an <m>R</m>-module of the direct sum of <m>n</m>-copies of <m>R</m>, i.e.,
			<me>R^{(n)}=\underbrace{R\oplus R\oplus\cdots\oplus R}_{n-\text{times}}.</me>
		</statement>
	</convention>
	<definition xml:id="def-minimal-generating-subset">
		<title>(Minimal generating subset and the rank of a module)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>M</m> be a finitely generated left <m>R</m>-module. Suppose that <m>m_1,m_2,\ldots,m_r\in M</m> are such that <m>M=Rm_1+\cdots+Rm_r</m>. We call <m>\{m_1,\ldots,m_r\}</m> a <term>generating subset</term> of <m>M</m>. By Well-ordering principle, there exists a minimal generating subset of <m>M</m>, such a generating subset is called a <term>minimal generating subset of <m>M</m></term>. The cardinality of a minimal generating subset of <m>M</m> is called the <term>rank of <m>M</m></term>. The rank of <m>M</m> is denoted by <m>{\rm rank}(M)</m>.
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="def-free-module-of-finite-rank">
		<title>(Free module of a finite rank)</title>
		<statement>
			An <m>R</m>-module <m>M</m> is said to be a <term>free module of a finite rank</term> if <m>M</m> is <m>R</m>-module isomorphic to <m>R^{(n)}</m> for some natural number <m>n</m>.
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="def-R-independence">
		<title>(<m>R</m>-linearly independence)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>M</m> be an <m>R</m>-mod, and let <m>m_1,\ldots,m_k\in M</m>. We say that <m>m_1,\ldots,m_k\in M</m> are <term><m>R</m>-linearly independent</term> if <m>r_1m_1+\cdots+r_km_k=0</m> then <m>r_1=r_2=\cdots=r_k=0\in R</m>.
			<p>
				Elements <m>x_1,\ldots,x_s\in M</m> are said to be <term><m>R</m>-linearly dependent</term> if <m>x_1,\ldots,x_s</m> are not <m>R</m>-linearly independent. In other words, <m>x_1,\ldots,x_s\in M</m> are <m>R</m>-linearly dependent if there are <m>r_1,\ldots,r_s\in R</m>, not all zero, such that <m>r_1x_1+\cdots+r_sx_s=0</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<example>
		<title>(Linear dependence of an element of a finite cyclic group)</title>
		<statement>
			Consider an abelian group <m>\Z/n\Z</m>, i.e., consider <m>\Z/n\Z</m> as a <m>\Z</m>-module. We show that any <m>[i]\in\Z/n\Z</m> is <m>\Z</m>-linearly independent. Indeed, for any <m>[i]\in\Z/n\Z</m> we have <m>n\cdot[i]=[0]</m>.
	</statement>
	</example>
</section>